</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="48" pageNumber="49" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1436,1010,1754]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,317,1082,1106]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Remarks:</emphasis>
See 
<tableCitation box="[370,491,1082,1106]" captionStart-0="TABLE 1" captionStart-1="TABLE 2" captionStart-2="TABLE 3" captionStartId-0="4.[151,232,984,1005]" captionStartId-1="5.[151,232,157,178]" captionStartId-2="5.[151,232,1139,1160]" captionText-0="TABLE 1. Frequency Distribution of Pectoral-Fin Rays in Species of Siphamia." captionText-1="TABLE 2. Frequency Distribution of Lateral-Line Scales to the end of the hypural plate in Species of Siphamia." captionText-2="TABLE 3. Frequency Distribution of Developed Gill Rakers in Species of Siphamia." pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Tables 1–3</tableCitation>
for frequency distributions of pectoral rays, lateral-line scales and gill rakers. 
<bibRefCitation author="Munro, I. S. R." pageId="48" pageNumber="49" refId="ref64488" refString="Munro, I. S. R. (1960) Handbook of Australian Fishes. pp. 138 - 140. Fisheries Newsletter (34)." type="book" year="1960">Munro (1960)</bibRefCitation>
counted 8 soft rays in the second dorsal fin of this species, but all the specimens we examined had 9 rays in this fin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1436,1010,1754]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
This is a small, compact species that belongs to the 
<taxonomicName box="[826,934,1190,1214]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Siphamia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tubifer">
<emphasis box="[826,934,1190,1214]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">S. tubifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group. Initially we thought it was misidentified small specimens of 
<taxonomicName box="[545,652,1226,1250]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Siphamia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tubifer">
<emphasis box="[545,652,1226,1250]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">S. tubifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as the two species share a complete lateral line, similar counts of developed gill rakers and a light organ that runs almost the full length of the caudal peduncle. However, radiographs of 
<taxonomicName box="[329,463,1298,1322]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Siphamia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="guttulata">
<emphasis box="[329,463,1298,1322]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">S. guttulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
revealed that it has two supraneural bones, a character it shares with 
<taxonomicName box="[1298,1428,1298,1322]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Siphamia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="argentea">
<emphasis box="[1298,1428,1298,1322]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">S. argentea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, whereas all other members of the 
<taxonomicName box="[532,635,1334,1358]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Siphamia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tubifer">
<emphasis box="[532,635,1334,1358]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">S. tubifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group have only one. It is also unique for the genus in having only one or no median predorsal scales. 
<bibRefCitation author="Gon, O. &amp; Randall, J. E." box="[496,766,1370,1394]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" pagination="1 - 49" refId="ref63655" refString="Gon, O. &amp; Randall, J. E. (2003) Revision of the Indo-Pacific cardinalfish genus Archamia (Perciformes: Apogonidae), with description of a new species. Indo-Pacific Fishes (35), 1 - 49." type="journal article" year="2003">Gon and Randall (2003)</bibRefCitation>
found a similar situation in the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="T.N.Gill" authorityYear="1863" box="[1192,1301,1370,1394]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Archamia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1192,1301,1370,1394]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Archamia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in which 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bleeker" baseAuthorityYear="1856" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Archamia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="buruensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">A. buruensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
had 1–2 median predorsal scales compared with 4–7 scales in other congeners.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1436,1010,1754]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
We have found only two lots of specimens for this species, both at the Australian Museum, Sydney, and both are 
<typeStatus box="[192,294,1479,1503]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">syntypes</typeStatus>
. 
<materialsCitation collectionCode="AMS" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" specimenCount="1" typeStatus="lectotype">
Of these the 
<quantity box="[447,546,1478,1502]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.25" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" unit="mm" value="22.5">22.5 mm</quantity>
SL specimen in 
<collectionCode box="[734,795,1478,1502]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">AMS</collectionCode>
IA.8103 is in relatively good condition, although it has a damaged caudal fin and two tubed lateral-line scales are missing on the left side. It is also unusual in having seven developed gill rakers on the lower part of the first gill arch. We designate this specimen as the 
<typeStatus box="[1269,1371,1550,1574]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">lectotype</typeStatus>
</materialsCitation>
<materialsCitation collectionCode="AMS" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" specimenCount="1" typeStatus="paralectotype">
of 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Apogonidae" genus="Siphamia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="guttulata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">S. guttulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The specimens in 
<collectionCode box="[469,530,1586,1610]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">AMS</collectionCode>
I.16306 therefore become 
<typeStatus box="[832,997,1586,1610]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">paralectotypes</typeStatus>
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1436,1010,1754]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
This species is known only from Darnley Island (
<figureCitation box="[761,829,1622,1646]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1283,1306]" captionTargetBox="[219,1369,553,1262]" captionTargetId="figure-1223@15.[219,1369,553,1262]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 8. Distribution of Siphamia argentea, S. cyanophthalma, S. fraseri, S. fuscolineata, S. guttulata, S. randalli, S. senoui, S. spinicola and S. tubulata." pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
), the 
<typeStatus box="[895,943,1623,1647]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">type</typeStatus>
locality, where it was found aggregating in rock crevices in shallow water. Smallest female with large gonad and eggs was 
<quantity box="[1042,1145,1658,1682]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.27" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" unit="mm" value="22.7">22.7 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
